post_text: Whenever USD 305 students are learning remotely, food service is available in a drive-thru, to-go format. The meals will be distributed out of Central High School’s Kitchen II, Monday through Friday from 11:00 a.m. to 12:30 p.m. The student's meal card must be scanned at the drive-thru site though students do not need to be present. (But parents/guardians must have the meal card.) Meals will be offered at the student's current eligibility category (e.g. free, reduced, paid).

post_text:
Flexibility is required in order to manage our way through the COVID-19 pandemic. Our on-site learning option is no exception. In on-site, learning can shift between three different models, in step with community restrictions. 1) On-site, a traditional face-to-face experience with precautions; 2) Hybrid, an alternating between on-site and off-site learning at reduced capacity (50%); 3) Off-site, an online learning model when community restrictions are high. Flexibility is built into the on-site learning option.
Find more information here: https://www.usd305.com/cms/One.aspx?portalId=11937719&pageId=14872173

post_text:
On July 15, USD 305 parents and guardians received an email reporting that Governor Kelly announced that she will issue an Executive Order that school will not start until September 9. The order will be issued on Monday, July 20 and we won’t know more details until we can review the actual order.

The delay of school starting will give USD 305 staff additional time to work with the Saline County Health Department as they monitor the status of COVID-19 in our community. It also allows time to continue planning for the safe return of our students and staff.

This is a rapidly changing situation. As soon as the Governor’s actual order has been released, we will review it and determine how to best proceed for Salina students and families. Once we have details to share, we will update you. Thank you.
text:
On July 15, USD 305 parents and guardians received an email reporting that Governor Kelly announced that she will issue an Executive Order that school will not start until September 9. The order will be issued on Monday, July 20 and we won’t know more details until we can review the actual order.

The delay of school starting will give USD 305 staff additional time to work with the Saline County Health Department as they monitor the status of COVID-19 in our community. It also allows time to continue planning for the safe return of our students and staff.

This is a rapidly changing situation. As soon as the Governor’s actual order has been released, we will review it and determine how to best proceed for Salina students and families. Once we have details to share, we will update you. Thank you.

post_text:
In early 2020, community members shared input about USD 305 at Strategic Planning Listening Sessions. All the comments are posted on our website.

We appreciate the time participants dedicated to these important conversations, which produced nearly 3,000 comments. The input will help us develop priorities that fit our community.

On June 16, the Board of Education reviewed the comments. District administrators and the board will incorporate the input into future direction for USD 305. Next steps include
• Focus Action, Summer/Fall 2020
• Implement Plans, Spring 2021
• Report Progress, Fall 2021

Please continue to check the http://ow.ly/9AZC50AbKOP website for updates about the strategic planning process. Thank you to all who participated!

The Friends of the River Foundation is taking their educational puppet show online, with help from a grant from the Greater Salina Community Foundation.
To teach elementary school children about wildlife found on the Smoky Hill River, the Friends of the River Foundation uses puppets designed by Spartle Twee Puppet Factory for the Salina Arts and Humanities Arts Infusion Program.
Bella Beaver, Bartholomew Bullfrog and the Great Blue Heron puppets teach Kindergarten through second grade students about river ecosystems and the animals who live there.
Now, instead of performing in classrooms, the puppets are entering children’s lives through social media.
Check it out!

post_text:
Superintendent Linn Exline and teacher Melinda Jett cover a lot of ground in episode 3 of Talk305. Melinda describes “What if…” concerns resulting from the news that the last quarter would not be face-to-face with students because of COVID-19. They talk about adapting, discovering opportunities to grow as well as what was missed. Melinda Jett is in her eighth year teaching at Salina Central and cherishes letters and emails from her students. She explains, “Working with teenagers, it is so difficult to read them sometimes. Until... you get those
sweet letters at the end of the year. The fact that they take the time to thank you is something that really makes my heart swell, and those notes are cherished and so appreciated. I’ve kept them all.”
You can find the podcast on the usd305.com website.

https://www.usd305.com/podcast

post_text:
We are so proud to share that Cottonwood Elementary School was a part of a virtual recognition ceremony today! They received a Shifting School Culture award for their Family University. Family University connects parents and caregivers with training and access to skills. Collaboration with community and school resources is an important ingredient in the recipe. We celebrate Cottonwood’s success!
How has this program affected over the past several weeks? Kyle Griffitts, principal, reports that they have been visiting homes checking on families, in a safe, distanced way. He shared, “We are still meeting with students for social/emotional needs, online, with the counselor and social worker. If anything, COVID has made us more aware of not only educating and building relationships with the student, but their family as well.” Congratulations Cottonwood staff! #Why305 Cottonwood Elementary PTA

post_text:
All of us are looking for new ways to connect since the pandemic took away a lot of our in-person conversations, handshakes, high fives and hugs. While videos and other messages cover a lot of ground, some topics deserve a deeper dive. This is why we’re creating a new podcast titled Talk305.

For this first podcast, hear from Jacy Murphy as she discusses her virtual kindergarten classroom through Meadowlark Ridge Elementary. Jacy talks about ways she connects with her young students. She tells of a lesson about baby animals where students were asked to find examples in their own environment. In his own backyard, one student saw a family of three baby bunnies and dictated to his mother a report for Jacy. The student’s mother was able to capture the moment on her phone and sent the attached picture to Jacy.

Superintendent Linn Exline hosts the conversation with Jacy on this new podcast that explores the heart of education. You can find the podcast on the usd305.com website. If you have an idea for a podcast topic, comment on this post! #Why305

https://www.usd305.com/podcast

shared_text:
City of Salina
April 1 at 12:55 PM ·

It’s Census Day! Quick Facts About the U.S. Census
• Population numbers derived from the decennial census are used to distribute over $6 billion in federal funds to Kansas every year.
• Every uncounted person costs the state of Kansas approximately $2,082 in federal funding.
• Census data is used to determine federal, state and local voting districts.
• Government, businesses and other stakeholders use census data for infrastructure and transportation planning; emergency preparedness, disaster relief, education funding, health tracking and disease control, and a multitude of other things.
• Businesses and government agencies consider population trends when choosing places to locate, which in turn boosts economic growth.
• As the census is only a once-every-10-years process, it is crucial to get the count right. If Kansas is under counted we will be shortchanged for a decade.
#Kansas #ShapeYourFuture #2020Census #EveryOneCounts

shared_text:
Salina Emergency Aid Food Bank
March 17 at 2:48 PM ·

Many of you have called, emailed and messaged the Food Bank to see how you can help during this unprecedented time.

We are adjusting how we serve our clients based on the current KDHE & CDC recommendations. However, we remain committed to providing food to those in our community in need. We continue to accept donations.

Our list of most needed items include: Canned Fruit, Rice, Tuna, Tuna Helper, Pancake Mix, Syrup, Spaghetti, Cold Cereal, Bar Soap, Dish Soap, Household Cleaning Products. Donations may be brought to the warehouse door on the west side of the building. Thank You!

post_text:
Students at Lakewood Middle School followed some big Google footprints. Tracy Hutton, Career and Life Planning teacher at Lakewood, developed a “20 Time Project” for her students based on a Google practice. At Google, 20 percent of work time can be dedicated toward an employee’s innovative idea. In Tracy’s class, students are encouraged to pursue a creative interest as they learn on their own.
Creative thinking, initiative, planning, self-regulation, time management, problem solving, reflection and grit are just some of the skills this project fosters. Students are encouraged to be vulnerable and to try something that challenges them. What a great opportunity for student to develop important life and employability skills! Nice job, Tracy and students, and a great example of why we are #PublicSchoolProud. #Why305 #PSW2020 #PublicSchoolsWeek Lakewood Middle School

Communities are stronger and schools are better when we all work together to support public education. Join us for Public Schools Week, Feb. 24-28, 2020 by sharing about the value of public education.
Did you know that nine out of 10 students attend a public school? Public schools welcome every child— regardless of ability, race, wealth, language, country of origin or needs. In addition, our nation’s economic and social well-being is tied to public education.
Think about what public education means to you and your family and leave a comment below. Please join us in celebrating Public Schools Week by sharing. #PublicSchoolProud #Why305 #SalinaKS #PSW20 #SalinaPublicSchools #USD305 #KansasPublicSchools

You probably know that every 10 years, each person in the United States is counted as part of the census.

What you might not know is that your decision to participate in the upcoming census in April 2020 will have a huge impact on our community and our state for the next decade. Funding based on the census count affects education, school lunch programs, Head Start programs, nutrition programs, highway funds and more.

It is critical that everyone is counted! #Salinaks #everyonecounts

post_text:
Conferences are planned for February 12 and 13. For building specific information or If you have questions about the conferences please contact your student’s school office.

Some of our schools schedule appointments while at the high schools they offer Career and College Readiness conferences. Both Central and South high schools involve Individual Plans of Study (IPS) which connect career pathways and classes students choose to their plans after high school.

At all levels, Parent-Teacher conferences are a great opportunity to ask questions, find out how your child interacts with other children and learn what you can do to help your child succeed. Research tells us parent involvement positively affects students’ grades and test scores, enrollment in higher-level programs, promotion and credits, attendance, social skills, graduation and beyond.

There is no school for USD 305 students on February 13 and 14. There is no school for elementary students on Monday, February 17. We look forward to seeing you! #Why305

shared_text:
Salina Education Foundation
January 27 at 5:43 PM ·

Everyone wants to know: Who is Joe?

This is Joe’s Pet Project’s fifth 305 LIVE, and they are thrilled to be back. Rocking together for nearly two decades, Joe’s Pet Project (JPP) is one big happy musical experiment. Members are spread across the country and assemble several times a year to play shows and create new material in a fast-paced improvisational setting. The result is a five-piece jam band known for their euphoric live performances of diverse originals and eclectic covers. In Salina, JPP plays wherever the town will have them, be it headlining the Smoky Hill River Festival or playing on the back of a trailer bed. Together they wrote the rock theatre piece STILLWATER that premiered at Kansas City Repertory Theatre and was subsequently performed in concert at Joe’s Pub, NYC.

They are all proud products of the USD 305 school system, and no, no one’s named Joe. www.joespetproject.com

Stay tuned: tomorrow we will introduce all the members of Joe's Pet Project.
